&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Iron&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Iron is an essential nutrient required for the synthesis of hemoglobin, a protein in red blood cells responsible for oxygen transport in the body.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Iron deficiency leads to a condition called &lt;strong&gt;iron-deficiency anemia&lt;/strong&gt;, which directly reduces the oxygen-carrying capacity of blood.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The primary symptoms of iron-deficiency anemia include fatigue, weakness, pale skin, and shortness of breath due to insufficient oxygen supply to tissues.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Dietary sources of iron include red meat, poultry, fish, legumes, leafy green vegetables, and iron-fortified cereals.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Iron absorption is enhanced by vitamin C, whereas substances like calcium and phytates can inhibit its absorption.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hemoglobin:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Hemoglobin is a protein in red blood cells that binds to oxygen in the lungs and transports it to tissues throughout the body.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Each hemoglobin molecule contains iron, which is critical for its oxygen-binding capacity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Iron-Deficiency Anemia:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A condition where the body lacks sufficient iron to produce adequate amounts of hemoglobin.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is the most common type of anemia globally and can affect people of all ages.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Types of Iron:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Heme iron: Found in animal-based foods like meat and is more easily absorbed by the body.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Non-heme iron: Found in plant-based foods and has lower bioavailability compared to heme iron.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Iron Absorption:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Vitamin C-rich foods like oranges and tomatoes enhance iron absorption.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Calcium, tea, coffee, and whole grains may inhibit iron absorption when consumed together with iron-rich foods.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Prevention and Treatment:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Preventing iron deficiency involves consuming a balanced diet rich in iron and vitamin C.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Iron supplements may be prescribed in cases of severe deficiency, under medical supervision.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;It is a weak base&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;HF (hydrofluoric acid) is classified as a weak acid because it does not completely dissociate into its ions in an aqueous solution.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;According to the Bronsted-Lowry theory, the strength of a conjugate base is inversely related to the strength of its parent acid.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Since HF is a weak acid, its conjugate base (F⁻) has a relatively low tendency to accept protons, making it a &lt;strong&gt;weak base&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Weak acids like HF have conjugate bases that are stronger than the conjugate bases of strong acids but are still not strong enough to be classified as strong bases.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;F⁻ has a modest ability to accept protons due to its high electronegativity, which contributes to its weak basic nature.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Acid and Base Strength:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A strong acid dissociates completely in water, producing a negligible conjugate base (e.g., HCl and Cl⁻).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A weak acid only partially dissociates, resulting in a conjugate base with measurable basicity (e.g., HF and F⁻).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Conjugate Acid-Base Pairs:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These are pairs of molecules or ions that differ by a single proton (H⁺).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For example, HF (acid) and F⁻ (base) form a conjugate acid-base pair.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Role of Electronegativity:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Fluoride ion (F⁻) is highly electronegative, which limits its ability to accept protons, contributing to its weak basicity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;pKa and pKb Relationship:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The strength of an acid (pKa) and its conjugate base (pKb) are related: pKa + pKb = 14 (at 25&amp;deg;C).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A weak acid like HF has a higher pKa, so its conjugate base (F⁻) has a lower pKb, indicating weak basicity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of HF and F⁻:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;HF is widely used in industrial processes such as glass etching and metal cleaning.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;F⁻ is used in fluoride treatments for dental health and in water fluoridation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3 pairs of false ribs&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Humans have a total of &lt;strong&gt;12 pairs of ribs&lt;/strong&gt;, which are divided into three categories: &lt;strong&gt;true ribs&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;false ribs&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;floating ribs&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;false ribs&lt;/strong&gt; are the &lt;strong&gt;8th, 9th, and 10th pairs&lt;/strong&gt; of ribs, located above the floating ribs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These ribs are called &amp;quot;false ribs&amp;quot; because they are not directly attached to the sternum; instead, they are connected to each other by &lt;strong&gt;costal cartilage&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;floating ribs&lt;/strong&gt; (11th and 12th pairs) are not attached to the sternum or any other ribs and are located below the false ribs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This arrangement provides flexibility and protection to vital organs such as the &lt;strong&gt;lungs&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;heart&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, there are &lt;strong&gt;3 pairs of false ribs&lt;/strong&gt; located above the floating ribs.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;True Ribs&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The first &lt;strong&gt;seven pairs of ribs&lt;/strong&gt; are called &lt;strong&gt;true ribs&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They are directly attached to the &lt;strong&gt;sternum&lt;/strong&gt; via costal cartilage.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;True ribs provide the primary support to the thoracic cage.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Floating Ribs&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;11th and 12th pairs&lt;/strong&gt; of ribs are called &lt;strong&gt;floating ribs&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These ribs are not attached to the sternum or other ribs, which makes them &amp;quot;floating.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Floating ribs serve to protect the &lt;strong&gt;kidneys&lt;/strong&gt; and other posterior organs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Flower, Seed and Fruit.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About Plant Reproduction&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;  &quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sexual Reproduction&lt;/strong&gt; is defined as the &lt;strong&gt;production of a (New organism)&lt;/strong&gt; from &lt;strong&gt;Two-parents&lt;/strong&gt; by using their &lt;strong&gt;(Gametes or Sex cells)&lt;/strong&gt;. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;  &quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Plants&lt;/strong&gt; also have &lt;strong&gt;Male and Female sex organs.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;  &quot;&gt;These plants are called &lt;strong&gt;(A&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;ngiosperms&amp;nbsp;or Flowering plants)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;  &quot;&gt;as they reproduce by the &lt;strong&gt;Sexual reproduction method.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;  &quot;&gt;Most of the plants contain &lt;strong&gt;Reproductive organs of both (Males&amp;nbsp;and Females) in the flowers.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&lt;strong&gt; (Male organ part) &lt;/strong&gt;of a flower is called the &lt;strong&gt;(Stamen)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;and the&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;(Female organ part) &lt;/strong&gt;of a flower is called &lt;strong&gt;(Carpel).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These &lt;strong&gt;Pollen Grains&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;help&amp;nbsp;in making&lt;strong&gt; (Male Gametes)&lt;/strong&gt; of the&lt;strong&gt; plant &lt;/strong&gt;and are &lt;strong&gt;present in Anther&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;(Male Gametes) &lt;/strong&gt;fertilize the &lt;strong&gt;(Female Gametes)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;fertilized&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;(Egg cells)&lt;/strong&gt; grow in&lt;strong&gt; Ovules &lt;/strong&gt;and become &lt;strong&gt;Seeds&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When &lt;strong&gt;germinated&lt;/strong&gt;, these &lt;strong&gt;Seeds&lt;/strong&gt; started growing as &lt;strong&gt;(new Plants)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Image of the Plant Reproduction:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;Diagram of the Parts of a Flower | Parts of a flower, Flower structure,  Diagram of a flower&quot; src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/21/02/F1_Utkarsha%20Singh_Anil_03.02.21_D1.png&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Notes:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;discovery of Sex in Plants&lt;/strong&gt; was &lt;strong&gt;noted by&amp;nbsp;two-person {Camerarius and Koelreuter}&lt;/strong&gt; in&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;1761&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/mistake-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Mistake Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Seeds and fruits are formed from parts of flowers after fertilization process of sexual reproduction in plants.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, flowers, seeds and fruits all participate in the sexual reproduction process.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Androecium&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The androecium is the &lt;strong&gt;male reproductive part&lt;/strong&gt; of a flower and consists of stamens.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A stamen is composed of two main components: the &lt;strong&gt;anther&lt;/strong&gt; (which produces pollen grains) and the &lt;strong&gt;filament&lt;/strong&gt; (a stalk that holds the anther).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The androecium plays a critical role in the flower&amp;#39;s reproduction process by producing &lt;strong&gt;male gametes&lt;/strong&gt; (pollen grains).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The pollen grains produced by the anther are transferred to the stigma of the female reproductive organ (gynoecium) during pollination.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Androecium can exist as a single stamen or multiple stamens depending on the flower&amp;#39;s structure and species.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gynoecium:&lt;/strong&gt; It is the female reproductive part of a flower, consisting of one or more carpels. Each carpel includes an ovary, style, and stigma.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Petals:&lt;/strong&gt; These are colorful parts of a flower that attract pollinators but do not play a direct role in reproduction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sepals:&lt;/strong&gt; These are the outermost parts of a flower that protect the budding flower before it blooms.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pollination:&lt;/strong&gt; The process by which pollen from the male part (androecium) is transferred to the female part (gynoecium) of a flower to facilitate fertilization.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Complete and Incomplete Flowers:&lt;/strong&gt; Flowers containing all four whorls (sepals, petals, androecium, and gynoecium) are termed complete, while those missing one or more whorls are incomplete.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
